bias, which ensures that a hypothetical threat will always outcompete a reassuring fact. Sociologists might invoke the information cascade, in which people abandon their own judgment in favor of the crowd’s apparent certainty.\n\nYou don’t need a degree to recognize what happened here. You just need to notice that at no point amid the warnings, the rumors, the color-coded paranoia, did anyone produce clear evidence of these supposed массов altercations actually occurring.\nThe “Red vs. Blue” fights were less an event than a mirror. They reflected our tendency to confuse visibility with validity, repetition with reality. They revealed how quickly a question can become a narrative, and how eagerly we participate in its spread, especially when it feels urgent or alarming.\n\nIn the end, the schools remained standing. The students, for the most part, remained uncolor-coordinated. And the great nationwide clash dissolved as quietly as it began, leaving behind only a digital paper trail of concern.\n\nIf there’s a lesson here, it’s not just about skepticism, though a little wouldn’t hurt. It’s about recognizing that in an age of constant connectivity, the line between “something is happening” and “people are talking about something happening” has never been thinner.\n\nSometimes, the loudest crisis is the one that never existed at all.",
