    "body": "Breaking news from the lab: scientists have discovered lasers that can flip magnets without heating them. Immediately, the internet did what it does best: panic, fantasize, and imagine a world where every human with a spoon in their blood becomes a walking fridge magnet.\n\nLet’s set the record straight: you are not about to stick to your refrigerator or attract paperclips with your veins. Sorry, Marvel fans.\n\nHere’s why:\nYour body is not a giant iron nugget. Sure, there’s iron in your blood. But it’s chemically bound inside hemoglobin. That’s science-talk for “it’s busy carrying oxygen, not practicing magnet tricks.” Also, the iron isn’t ferromagnetic; it won’t flip polarity with a laser, even if you’re late for work and really, really need to stick to something.\nLasers are picky eaters. The laser that flips magnets only affects solid ferromagnetic materials like nickel or cobalt in lab settings. Your jewelry, piercings, or leftover metallic nutrients? Not on the menu. Sorry to disappoint, aspiring human compass enthusiasts.\n\nAir, water, and food aren’t secret magnets. Trace metals in our environment are mostly aluminum, zinc, and copper. These metals are as magnetic as a wet noodle; that is, not at all. Your smoothie won’t turn you into a living magnet, and your salad won’t make you stick to the fridge.\n\nScience vs. Sci-Fi. Yes, the research is groundbreaking for future computing and memory storage. No, it’s not a secret weapon to turn us into magnetized superheroes. The laser’s power is microscopic and highly controlled. You won’t wake up with a ferromagnetic twin inside you.\nSo, next time someone whispers, “The scientists are secretly training us to become human fridge magnets,” just smile, nod, and remind them: science is exciting, lasers are cool, but we are still not part of a Marvel experiment.\n\nIn fact, the real takeaway? This technology is about computing, not human levitation. We can cheer for lasers flipping magnets in a lab without fearing that our breakfast cereal will stick to our faces.\nNow go enjoy your toast without worrying about becoming Iron Man.",
