    "topic": "No, You Are Not Eating Spiders in Your Sleep",
    "body": "As you fall asleep, you remember the myth: eight spiders a year, in your mouth, while you sleep.  Suddenly, you’re awake again, lips sealed like Fort Knox, questioning reality.\n\nLet’s fix that.\n\nThis cursed little nugget of internet folklore is spectacularly, hilariously false.\n\nFirst of all: who started this rumor and why do they hate peace?\n\nThe spider statistic did not come from scientists.\nIt did not come from sleep studies.\nIt did not come from spiders.\n\nIt came from a journalism experiment in the 1990s meant to prove that people will believe anything if it sounds vaguely scientific and mildly horrifying.\n\nMission accomplished, the internet saw “you eat spiders in your sleep,” and everyone had an arachnophobia meltdown.\n\nLet’s talk about spiders for a second.\n\nSpiders are not: curious about humans, attracted to mouths, interested in carbon dioxide blasts, or thrilled by sudden jaw twitches.\n\nSpiders are extremely cautious, vibration-sensitive, and risk-averse introverts.\n\nTo a spider, your face is not a cozy Airbnb; it is a wind tunnel attached to a malfunctioning earthquake.\n\nYour mouth is not the five-star dining destination they’re looking for.\n\nImagine being a spider and thinking:\n\n“Ah yes, a large, warm creature that breathes erratically, snores like a chainsaw, and occasionally clenches its teeth. Perfect.”\n\nIf spiders were routinely crawling into human mouths, someone would have woken up with a crushed spider in their mouth. \n\nThe math alone should’ve saved us.\n\nIf everyone ate eight spiders a year:\n\nBillions of spiders would be disappearing annually.\n\nSpiders would be proven to have a deeply flawed survival instinct.\n\nSomeone would’ve noticed by now, and there would be documentaries, trauma support groups, along with tiny spider warning labels on pillows.\n\nThere are none.\n\nSo why does this myth refuse to die?\n\nBecause it has everything the internet loves:\n\nDisgust ✅\n\nFear ✅\n\n“Fun fact” energy ✅\n\nZero requirement to verify anything ✅\n\nIt’s the same reason we believed that goldfish forget everything, the Great Wall is visible from space, and bald eagles hitch rides on black bear backs, across vast bodies of water.  \n\nIf it sounds cool, outlandishly interesting, or creepy enough, it spreads like wildfire on the internet.\n\nThe real lesson here is that you are not eating spiders in your sleep.\nYou never were.\nYou never will.\n\nYou are living in an age where misinformation can seep into your brain while you’re awake, no eight-legged creatures required.\n\nSo the next time someone whispers, “Did you know you eat spiders in your sleep?”\nYou can smile peacefully and say:\n\n“No. But I do swallow bad internet facts if I’m not careful.”\n\nSleep well, the spiders are avoiding you.",
