    "date": "2025-12-15",
    "title": "End of the World: Buy 9, Get the 10th Free.",
    "topic": "The World Has Ended Again. We Must Have Missed It.",
    "body": "By now, the apocalypse has missed its appointment so many times it should probably stop calling. According to the internet, the world has “definitively” ended dozens of times in the past few decades, sometimes quietly, sometimes in spectacular fashion, and always with complete confidence.\n\nTake the now-debunked claim that a global six-minute blackout would plunge Earth into darkness on August 2, 2025, supposedly triggered by a rare solar eclipse. The story raced through social media feeds with the urgency of an emergency broadcast. NASA, meanwhile, calmly pointed out that no such eclipse existed, no blackout was predicted, and the planet would continue doing what it has done for 4.5 billion years: not ending on schedule.\n\nIt was hardly the first time.\n\nIn 2012, millions braced for extinction when a misreading of the Mayan calendar convinced the internet that December 21 marked the end of time. When the sun rose the next day, the calendar, unlike the theory, was revealed to be perfectly functional.\n\nIn 1999, Y2K panic warned that computers would fail at midnight, planes would fall from the sky, and civilization would reset to the Stone Age. The clocks rolled over, the lights stayed on, and the biggest casualty was bottled water sales, ironically skyrocketing.\n\nThen there was 2011, when radio preacher Harold Camping predicted the Rapture not once, but twice. When May came and went, the date was simply rescheduled. When October passed, the apocalypse quietly retired without comment.\n\nOther near misses include the mysterious Planet X (also known as Nibiru), which has allegedly been on a collision course with Earth since at least 2003. It has failed to arrive every single time. CERN was supposed to create a planet-devouring black hole. Yellowstone was supposed to explode on YouTube’s schedule. The Large Hadron Collider, solar flares, rogue asteroids, alien invasions, and even Facebook glitches have all been promoted as the final chapter of human history.\n\nAnd yet, here we are. Again.\n\nWhat makes these stories spread isn’t scientific plausibility; it’s emotional velocity. They’re dramatic, urgent, and oddly entertaining. A claim doesn’t need to be true to go viral; it just needs to feel big. Deepfake videos of world leaders declaring emergencies that never happened, AI-generated disaster clips mistaken for reality, or recycled hoaxes like “Good morning images contain malware” continue to thrive because they trigger instant reactions before critical thinking catches up.\n\nThe humor lies in the pattern. Every apocalypse arrives with certainty, countdown clocks, and authoritative-sounding language. Every apocalypse leaves without explanation. No apologies. No refunds.\n\nBut beneath the comedy is a real lesson. Social media rewards shock, not accuracy. Algorithms amplify fear faster than facts. And when people share before verifying, misinformation doesn’t just spread, it performs.\n\nThe world ending makes for great content. The world continues, less so.\n\nSo the next time the internet announces that Earth has 48 hours left, take a breath. Check a source. Maybe make a sandwich. History suggests the planet will still be here when you’re done eating.\n\nAfter all, if the Creator wanted to destroy the Earth, if the world really were ending, it probably wouldn’t announce itself via a forwarded post with three emojis and a countdown timer.\n\nAnd if it does? Well, based on past performance, it’ll likely reschedule.",
